Here’s a simple style block you can drop into either a basic web template or most Markdown‑to‑HTML/PDF tools; the same values can also be turned into paragraph and heading styles inside Word.

---

### **Option 1 – CSS Snippet (for HTML / Markdown Export)**

```css
body {
  background-color: #F9F9F9;
  color: #222222;
  font-family: "Open Sans", Arial, sans-serif;
  margin: 2em;
}

h1, h2, h3 {
  color: #4EA1A6;
  font-family: "Open Sans Semibold", Arial, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
}

hr {
  border: none;
  border-top: 2px solid #5B7FA6;
  margin: 1.2em 0;
}

footer {
  font-size: 0.85em;
  color: #555555;
  text-align: center;
  margin-top: 2em;
}
```

Drop this into the header of your Markdown export or HTML document, and it will produce the calm teal‑and‑gray layout we discussed.  

---

### **Option 2 – Word / LibreOffice Style Table**

| Element | Font / Size | Color | Notes |
|----------|--------------|--------|-------|
| Title banner | Open Sans Semibold 18 pt | Teal #4EA1A6 | Centered, uppercase |
| Heading 2 | Open Sans Semibold 13 pt | Slate #5B7FA6 | Left‑aligned |
| Body text | Open Sans Regular 11 pt | Charcoal #222222 | 1.25 × line spacing |
| Footer | Open Sans Regular 9 pt | Gray #555555 | Centered, narrow margins |

---

These small style rules will keep your **Tone & Timing Reference Sheet** readable and visually consistent whether it’s printed, sent as a PDF, or shown on slides.  

